title: For Sale:  Best of Luck
postcontent:
Okay, let's go over the problems here...

"Looking for law abiding citizens who believe that the constitution is your Right not Your privilege .we are excepting application from all walks of life that love the outdoors ,tactical shooting , ect ect . Please have yr own gear (kit) would like to patrol the boarder (Canadian )"

"Looking for law-abiding citizens who believe the constitution is a right, not a privilege" is probably better than what you've got but still conveys your message. Remember though, the Constitution and the subsequent Bill of Rights are actually what define our rights. They are not rights, they are documents. Also, since the Constitution and Bill of Rights are proper nouns they need to be capitalized. "We are accepting (not "excepting") applications from all walks of life, looking for people interested in the outdoors, tactical shooting, etc..." is an improvement as well. For future reference commas come directly after the word, with no space in between the word and the comma. The same applies to periods. Also "etcetera" is abbreviated "etc", not "ect". "Please have your own equipment. I would like to patrol the Canadian border (not 'boarder')" sounds a little better. The problem comes when you put the whole message together...
 
  "Looking for law-abiding citizens who believe the Constitution is a right, not a privilege. We are accepting applications from all walks of life, looking for people interested in the outdoors, tactical shooting, etc... Please have your own equipment. I would like to patrol the Canadian border."
   
     Now don't get me wrong. I support your right to do this, and to recruit, and freedom of speech. What bugs me is you're basically saying (in poor English)...

"Folks with guns wanted from all walks of life to form a group to defend the state with the least need of civil defense from a country that has less hostile intent than the Principality of Monaco. We would wander the woods with assorted gear in potentially bad weather (you want to get started before next June right?) where the border isn't clearly marked, putting ourselves at repeated risk of civil, criminal, and federal charges in 2 sovereign nations for no particularly good reason." 
    
 Hell, I even support the idea of a "well regulated militia" composed of people not under federal jurisdiction; but this is not how to go about it. If you want to get people with half a brain on your side you have to sound like you have at least 3/4s of one. Nice flag though.

postcontent:
I purchased this rail brand new for my Savage 10 Precision Carbine, only to discover that it will not work with my particular scope. It was mounted very briefly and then removed. I ordered a new set of mounting screws from TPS, so it'll come with both the original (used) screws and four brand new screws. This is a very high-quality precision STEEL rail and is basically new with the original packaging. Asking $50 OBO, pickup only in Dallas, either downtown or near the Arboretum.

This rail is elevated by a 20 MOA cant. So when you mount your scope, you will have to adjust the reticle 20 MOA lower than you otherwise would in order to zero it in. This means that you'll have an extra 20 MOA of upward adjustment, allowing you to adjust the reticle to shoot longer distances. This rail will work on all Savage models 10 through 16 with the round rear receiver, for both the regular short action receivers, as well as the Axis receivers. Manufacturer's description follows:

The TPS XP 1-Piece Picatinny-Style Scope Base provides a standard in quality that only Tactical Precision Systems can deliver. The XP scope rail features a integral recoil shoulder to eliminate the base from moving under heavy recoil. It has a full length Mil-STD 1913 (Picatinny) rail, built to military specifications, as well as being fully compatible with Weaver-style rings. The entire scope rail is CNC machined, with the same standards and quality as all of the products from TPS. The scope rail is machined from a solid billet of 1215 alloy steel. The steel rail is finished in a matte black oxide finish to Mil-C-13924 standards. The XP bases are supplied with four 6-48 Torx screws and wrench for reliable and trouble-free installation.

title: For Trade:  Taurus Model 44
postcontent:
For trade only. Taurus 44 Magnum, 6.5 inch ported barrel, 6 shot cylinder. This gun, in my opinion, is extremely fun if you like shooting big calibers and is a manageable 44 mag. I'd say that if handguns in 45acp or 357 mag don't phase you then the kick from this shouldn't be a problem. That said, I wouldn't recommend this for beginners.

I'm in no rush to give this away and would be happy keeping it. I got it in what I think was a great trade for both myself and the other person. I'm just looking to see if I can trade straight up for other firearms that have been at the top of my wanted list, shown below. I've seen how much a factory new Model 44 costs and while this one has been used I can say that, after putting 100 rds of 44 mag through it myself, it's good as new and performs brilliantly. I wouldn't put a gun up for sale or trade if it didn't.

A straight up trade is my goal as I'm not looking to add cash with mine, at least not too much. I could add some if what you offer REALLY interests me and we both agree on the amount. For those who want this and offer something that interests me but is maybe a couple hundred less than what the Taurus would be, I'm willing to work with you but please be prepared to add that amount with your trade. 

I'm in Navarre and will only drive as far west-northwest as the Pensacola, Cantonment or Milton areas and as far east as Fort Walton or Destin. I'd rather we meet at a halfway point but we can figure something out. Email or text only, no calls as I work different shifts. REDACTED. Thanks.
